				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">In Last-Ditch Effort for Alstom, Siemens and Mitsubishi Heavy Raise Offer</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By David Jolly			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-06-20T06:41:02+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">June 20, 2014 2:41 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">June 20, 2014 2:41 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/06/20/in-last-ditch-effort-duo-raises-offer-in-bid-for-alstom/" data-title="In Last-Ditch Effort for Alstom, Siemens and Mitsubishi Heavy Raise Offer" data-description="Siemens and Mitsubishi Heavy said they were raising the cash component of their offer for Alstom, the French industrial company at the center of their takeover battle with General Electric.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">PARISÂ â The top executives of Siemens and General Electric on Friday made what were likely to be their final pitches to the French government in their <a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/06/20/france-to-back-g-e-s-bid-for-alstom-assets/" title="France to Back G.E.âs Bid for Alstom Assets">battle for Alstom, the French industrial company</a> at the center of a high-stakes political battle.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Jeffrey R. Immelt, General Electric&#8217;s chairman and chief executive, met with President FranÃ§ois Hollande at the ÃlysÃ©e Palace in the afternoon. A short while later, Joe Kaeser, Mr. Immelt&#8217;s  counterpart at Siemens, met with the French leader.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The companies are competing to obtain Alstom&#8217;s energy businesses, which boast world-leading technology in power-generation equipment and electrical grids.<br />
â<br />
Earlier in the day, Siemens and its partner in the bid, Mitsubishi Heavy Industries, said that they were raising the cash component of their offer, in a last-ditch effort to swing the contest their way.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Hollande&#8217;s government was caught flat-footed in late April to find that Alstom, one of the country&#8217;s top manufacturers with annual revenue of 20 billion euros, or $27 billion, was in talks to sell its energy businesses to G.E. for $13.5 billion.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Citing concerns about technology, national energy independence and French jobs, Economy Minister Arnaud Montebourg sought a competing bid from Siemens and Mitsubishi Heavy and decreed that the state would have the final say on any tie-up.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The German and Japanese companies made a preliminary proposal on Monday, and raised their offer on Friday morning, a day after G.E. substantially altered its own offer to assuage those concerns.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In their revised offer, Mitsubishi Heavy, based in Tokyo, and Siemens, based in Munich, said they addressed one of the main concerns of critics of their initial proposal by increasing the cash component of their offer. Now the companies are offering â¬8.2 billion instead of &#8364;7 billion.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">That move resulted in a value of Alstomâs energy businesses of  â¬14.6 billion, â¬400 million more than previously proposed.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">G.E. values the energy businesses at â¬12.35 billion. But because the American company  would walk away with the unitsâ cash, it would only pay â¬9.9 billion, which equates to the $13.5 million bid.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Under the new offer, Mitsubishi Heavy simplified the structure of its side of the deal. It would obtain under one holding company a 40 percent stake in Alstomâs combined steam-turbine, electric grid and hydroelectric power businesses.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Siemens would take over entirely Alstomâs business making turbines for the gas generation industry.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And the German company jettisoned the vague language it had previously used about a âgood faithâ effort to eventually combine its rail business with Alstomâs, saying it now âoffers to enter immediately into a joint venture for mobility management, including signaling between Alstom and Siemens.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In a statement, General Electric played down the significance of its rivalsâ action on Friday, citing Mr. Immelt as saying that even with the revised offer, G.E. was still offering more cash.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âIn addition,â G.E. said, âthe competitive bid is unrealistic because it splits Alstomâs gas and steam businesses and is not structured for the long-term success of Alstom.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In any case, the maneuvering appears to be entering its final stages. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Reuters reported that the government planned to make France&#8217;s position known on the rival offers at a news conference Friday night. â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">G.E has set a Monday deadline for Alstom&#8217;s board to accept its offer, and Mr. Immelt said Thursday that he was prepared to walk away if it was not met.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Alstom said Friday in a statement that its board would meet no later than Monday to review the two offers but that it planned no further communications on the process.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The new offer from Siemens and Mitsubishi is still not good enough to trump G.E.âs bid, said Zacharias Sautner, a professor at the Frankfurt School of Finance and Management.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âItâs clear from the shareholder perspective the G.E. offer is more attractive,â Mr. Sautner said Friday. âI think it will be the G.E. offer that will win.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">While political considerations in this case tend to be at least equal to the interests of Alstom shareholders, the French government has extracted the promises and concessions it wanted from G.E., Mr. Sautner said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As a result, he said, the way is clear for Alstomâs board to accept the American offer based on what is best for shareholders.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âIt would be a big stretch now if the French government would block it,â Mr. Sautner said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In its revised bid, G.E. would still get Alstomâs prized gas turbine business and its existing customer base.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But to maintain Franceâs presence in the energy business, G.E. would create two joint ventures with Alstom: one in the power grid business and another in renewable energy.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Sautner noted that in addition to that degree of French control, the government would retain licensing control over Alstom technology used in nuclear steam turbines.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The most recent offer by Siemens shows that the German company is not so desperate to acquire parts of Alstom that it is willing to throw caution to the wind, he said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âSiemens has been careful not to come up with a reckless offer,â Mr. Sautner said. âBoth parties are very rational bidders,â he said, referring to Siemens and G.E. âThey have been very careful not to get into a bidding war.â</p>
<div id="addendums" class="addendums"><div class="story-addendum theme-correction"><strong>Correction: June 20, 2014</strong> <br>An earlier version of this article misstated the amount by which Mitsubishi Heavy and Siemens were increasing their cash offer for French industrial company Alstom. Their offer increased the cash component by â¬1.2 billion, not from â¬1.2 billion.
